05085nam a22007335i 9780823291649DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232916497 a10.1515/97808232916492doi  a(DE-B1597)565923  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aFreud and Fundamentalism :bThe Psychical Politics of Knowledge /ced. by Stathis Gourgouris. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tModeling Freud and Fundamentalism -- tMyth and Dogma in 1920: The Fundamentalist-Modernist Controversy and Freud’s ‘‘Death Drive’’ -- tTrees, Pain, and Beyond: Freud on Masochism -- tOf Rats and Names -- tMad Country, Mad Psychiatrists: Psychoanalysis and the Balkan Genocide -- tEverything You Always Wanted to Know About David Lynch, but Should Be Afraid to Ask Slavoj Žižek -- tFictions of Possession: Psychoanalysis and the Occult -- tReligion and the Future of Psychoanalysis -- tThe Contribution of Psychoanalysis to Understanding the Genesis of Society -- tThe Hermeneutics of Suspicion Reconsidered -- tOn the Epistemological Status of Psychoanalysis -- tNote -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the heart of this volume are questions about the psychic components of the modes of thinking we call “fundamentalist”—that is, thinking that disavows multiplicities of meaning, abhors allegorical elements, and strives toward an exclusionary orthodoxy that codifies not just its own world but that of its adversaries, its others. The essays address transcendentalist orthodoxies of all kinds, whether religious or secularist. Fundamentalist elements in psychoanalysis itself are also placed in question, at the same time as psychoanalytic thinking and practice is explored as a mode of knowledge that ultimately unravels fundamentalist tendencies. The texts in this collection represent a wide array of disciplinary standpoints. Their overall aspiration is to interrogate discourses of orthodoxy, literalism, exclusion, and dogma—that is, discourses obsessed with monolithic (monolingual, monological, monolateral, monomythical, and certainly monotheistic) encounters with the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnidjar, Gil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArsić, Branka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaltas, Aristides, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjelić, Dušan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastoriadis, Cornelius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourgouris, Stathis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourgouris, Stathis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aParker, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRavetto-Biagioli, Kriss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenthal, Lecia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaubes, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhitebook, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum